Hi - this is an outdoor electrical cable connector - use it to permanently encapsulate a cable splice into a solid block of  resin to protect the joint from the elements.  Commercial versions of these are used in industry for underground cables.  
This one is free and customizable!  
Its good for low voltage - pool, garden lights, boats, underground sprinkler wiring etc - the original version I made about a year ago has been underwater for over 12 months with no signs of resin degradation or water ingress yet   
IMPORTANT: THIS IS FOR LOW VOLTAGE APPLICATIONS ONLY It's not safe for connecting domestic 115VAC or 240VAC supply - don't even think about it!   (use at own risk etc)  
Read more in the instructions tab for how to assemble and use.

You need:
a) polyurethane or epoxy resin + catalyst (available from any hardware or boat shop)
b) tape for both ends
c) tools to solder or join the wires Step 1 - customize and print out the size of connector shell you need - no support is needed to print - the funny little shapes are spacers to help locate the cable join right in the middle of the shell Step 2 - thread the cable through the joiner shell and out the top - splice the wires together by soldering or crimping. Consider putting heatshrink or tape over any exposed joins for added protection. Step 3 - fit the wires back into the shell - its extremely important to make sure the wires are not touching the sides and have sufficient space for the resin to fully encapsulate them. Use the little spacer things or small cable ties to hold the cable in place down the middle of the shell for the next steps (the spacers are designed to hang from the top of the shell) Step 4 - tape both ends - use tape that will stretch and form a tight 100% seal around the cable you're about to join so no resin will get out during the pour. Step 5 - follow the manufacturers directions to mix and pour resin into the shell - go slow and make sure there are no pockets or air bubbles. The resin needs to go right into the ends and all around around the cables where they enter the connector shell, then fill the shell right up to the top. Use a pin or piece of wire to work the resin into every nook and cranny. Step 6 - Clean up - cut off the ends from any spacers that are poking out from the top of the shell through the resin - that's it - you're done!

title: Not the Treyarch Logo Fidget Spinner

description.text:
Treyarch doesn't want there to be fidget spinners of their logo, so this is definitely not that. As you can see by the fact that I so easily placed a no smoking sign thing over a picture of their logo, this thing can't possibly be based on it. Would a computer let me lie to you? On the internet? I don't think so. Besides, the curvature is different. This is just a trefoil knot which has no relation whatsoever to the Treyarch logo. Wherever you got such a notion to begin with, I urge you to put it out of your mind immediately.

I have included two versions: One with and one without orbiting mounts for additional weights or bearings.

I have also included two OpenSCAD files: one for each version. You may adjust the degree to which the arms jut out by changing the pointiness variable. Any other changes are at your own risk. It should be noted that OpenSCAD will fail to render if a cylinder intersects with an intersection in the knot. Hence the thin inner mount ring. So if you want to create a knot with more points you'll have to comment out all cylinders and forgo using it as a spinner, unless you can work out the math to expand the center of the knot.

You'll need https://github.com/openscad/scad-utils and sweep.scad from https://github.com/openscad/list-comprehension-demos to use these scad files.

title: Anet A8 E3D V6 Direct Mount

description.text:
Check out my new website for finding filament print settings: 3DPrintingDB.com

My goal is to make it easy to find a starting point when using a new filament. Please let me know what you think!

This is an E3D V6 (genuine and clone) direct drive mount for the Anet A8 and AM8 printers. This replaces the black rectangular metal mount that holds the original extruder motor and hot end.

This mount re-uses the existing bearings and screws for connecting to the bearings. This should be printed in a temperature resistant material such as PETG or ABS

You will need the following parts:

  1. V6 style hotend
  2. Small piece of PTFE bowden tubing (roughly 4-5")
  3. 2x M3x18 or M3x20 screws
  4. 2x M3x30 screws
  5. 1x M4x10 hex bolt
  6. 6x M3 hex nuts
  7. Fan Shroud. I used this one: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1620630
Instructions
  1. Attach the 2x M3x30 belt holder screws to the mount. Tighten with an M3 hex nut.
  2. Screw the mount to the bearings on the Anet A8 using the original M4 screws
  3. Mount the blower fan onto the side of the mount using the original M3 screws and the two hex nuts. There is a hole in the opposite side of the mount that allows screw driver access.
  4. Using the M3x18 (or M3x20) screws and the printed clamp, attach the V6 hotend.
  5. Place the PTFE tubing through the hole in the top of the mount and into the hot end heat sink.
  6. Place the extruder motor (with the extruder parts) on top of the mount, running the PTFE tubing through the hole that leads to the filament gear. You will need to cut the PTFE tubing down so that it goes as close to the filament gear and pulley as possible without touching them.
  7. Once the PTFE tubing is the proper length, secure the extruder to the mount with the M4x10 hex bolt. Tighten it so that the extruder does not move.
  8. Clamp belt ends to the back of the mount on the belt screws. Place another M3 hex nut on each screw end to keep the belt from moving.
    Update Nov. 3, 2017

    Added clamp with mount for BLTouch or 3DTouch (Tested with 3DTouch).
    You can use the same mounting screws that the clamp used before. Need an additional two M3 screws and nuts to mount the probe. The probe offset from the nozzle is 0 X and -38 Y

description.text:
Is it golden? The 2D shape of Taiwan is extruded through the path of a golden spiral. The wave base is a golden rectangle. Golden Taiwan is not the current state of Taiwan. The name also implies a wish.

It's based on golden_spiral_extrude and bezier_surface modules of my library. I used a 2D shape of Taiwan here; however, the golden_spiral_extrude module can extrude any 2D shape.

Printer:

CR8

Rafts:

No

Yes

Resolution:

0.2 mm layer

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Scale: 0.55

I downloaded the vector map of Taiwan from Free Vector Maps, used Inkscape 0.92.1 with Inkscape to OpenSCAD converter v7 to generate a .scad file containing the path, and refactored the path into a shape_taiwan function.

Then, I tried to use the code below to generate the model. 

include <shape_taiwan.scad>;
include <circle_path.scad>;
include <rotate_p.scad>;
include <golden_spiral.scad>;
include <cross_sections.scad>;
include <polysections.scad>;
include <golden_spiral_extrude.scad>;
include <bezier_curve.scad>;
include <bezier_surface.scad>; 
include <function_grapher.scad>;

// Taiwan
mirror_taiwan = [for(pt = shape_taiwan(15)) [pt[0] * -1, pt[1]]];

translate([127.5, 42.5, 83]) golden_spiral_extrude(
    mirror_taiwan, 
    from = 1,  
    to = 10, 
    point_distance = 1,
    scale = 10
);

// wave
t_step = 0.05;
thickness = 100;

ctrl_pts = [
    [[0, 0, 20],  [60, 0, -35],   [90, 0, 60],    [200, 0, 5]],
    [[0, 50, 30], [100, 60, -25], [120, 50, 120], [200, 50, 5]],
    [[0, 100, 0], [60, 120, 35],  [90, 100, 60],  [200, 100, 45]],
    [[0, 123, 0], [60, 123, -35], [90, 123, 60],  [200, 123, 45]]
];

g = bezier_surface(t_step, ctrl_pts);

difference() {
    function_grapher(g, thickness);
    translate([-1, -1, -120]) cube([220, 130, 110]);
}

Even though I can render Taiwan or the wave base separately, OpenSCAD generates an error when rendering both. To solve this problem, I rendered and exported STLs separately and imported them into 3D Builder. After repairing the model, I saved the result as a new STL.

This thing allows for battery changes on the Dexcom G5 transmitter.

You'll need DIY skills to cut down (or mill flat) the G5 transmitter leaving 6.5mm to 6.7mm from the flat base (6.7 gives the tightest fit).
Then remove old batteries, as per the YouTube video. (Do a search)
Clean the contacts well. I use a small rotating wire brush in a hand held hobby grinder.
I've found there's no need for solder if you spring out the bottom contacts and form the top ones into a curve so that they will be pressed down to contact by the cover.
Put in 2 new 389 batteries or the 2mm thicker SR43W batteries (recommended for longer life for higher VA & VB values)
Clip on the cover.
Engraved one colour versions of both types have been added
Test the voltage across the 2 contacts as per the Youtube video
Add a bead of silicon to make it waterproof if required, this would need cutting with a blade before the next change.

Subsequent battery changes will just be a matter of unclipping, changing the batteries and clipping the cover back in.

You will need a smartphone with Xdrip+ installed.
Dexcom readers/software don't allow battery changes

I printed it in ABS on it's side using a raft & supports with 100% infill.
You may prefer to use nylon.

This is a new X carriage for the Anet A6 to fit a genuine E3D V6. It will require 2 M3 screws about 45mm long, and 2 M3 nuts to clamp the hotend in place. Walls: To create a strong part, it is advised to increase wall thickness.
Supports: Only needs support for embedded nuts, but may be fine without.
Orientation: print hotend clamp standing up and X-carriage with hotend clamp notch facing upward to minimize support.
Infill: 40% or more for a strong part.
Time: MyMiniFactory took 3 hours 50 mins to print all parts.

Remove supports and raft (if used). Insert bearings from original X carriage into the new one. Insert nuts into embedded holes, and screw bolts through the clamp to attach E3D v6 tightly into place. Attach the end stop to the X carriage (recommended by hot glue - if you want holes in design either drill them or ask me and I will change the design). Pass linear rails through bearings. Attach belt to slots at both ends tightly, and you're ready to print!

title: Ez Arduino MiniKame -  8 DOF Quadruped Robot

description.text:
Thing:1265766 is a cute robot. We remix it with our design thing:1912377 hopefully to be a neat and simple design. It is an implementation using Arduino board and cheap tower pro 9g servo. Thus, it is relatively inexpensive to make one,. With more details of guiding (see the assembling video at below), we believe it is much easier for people to make one.

Video Demos:

https://youtu.be/P3zWXnrXG6c
https://youtu.be/7D6HDkSJ0Co

Electronics:

1) GSTduino with on-board SPP-C-Bluetooth-UART board.
2a) a 3.7V lithium-polymer battery with XH2.54 connector, size W35mm, T40mm & L70mm, 1200mAh (see below photo as an example) or any dimension smaller.
2b) or 3.7V 18650 battery pack with XH2.54 connector, 3000mAh
2c) to charge the battery find our another design
3) 8 x Tower Pro 9g servo.
4) a 117s on/off switch
5) a SPP-C Bluetooth UART or equivalent for Andriod phone control. Baud rate sets to 115200. You don't need to buy separately if you use item 1.

We use GSTduino board here as it integrates everything on a single PCB. So It's a lot easier for people to make this bot. If you use other Arduino board such as nano, likely you will need a I/O shield for connecting servos. If you are experienced maker, of cause you can use a proto board to customized one. The body of robot is the chamber which can hold lithium-polymer battery. You may have to look after the power regulator too.

Hardware:

1) Dupoint wires
2) Some M2x6 tapping screws

Software:

1) Arduino code on githup
2) Android app on Google Play.

Arduino sketchup loading example:

https://youtu.be/hrOBFPLUjd4

These software will work on our another design thing:1912377. Perhaps you will be interested to build it too.

Wring:

Connection to digital pins of Arduino are as following -

1) D2 to front right hip servo
2) D3 to front right leg servo
3) D4 to back right hip servo
4) D5 to back right leg servo
5) D6 to back left hip servo
6) D7 to back left leg servo
7) D8 to front left hip servo
8) D9 to front left leg
9) D12 for setup mode (see the assemble video)
10) Bluetooth UART module to the board's Bluetooth connector

Printer:

prusa i3

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

10%

3.7V lithium-polymer battery, extra wire connector is soldered directly to the battery terminals. And be careful when soldering the wire to battery, take caution not shorting it. Battery charging with charger dock (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2398439) we design.

How to play:

When the robot is power on, it is in autonomous mode. In this mode, walking direction and pattern is randomly changed in every 8 sec.

It can be controlled by the Android phone with the Bluetooth UART module. To control by the App, firstly pair the Bluetooth UART with your Android phone and tap setting menu of app to select it. After bluetooth connection is ready, sliding the bottom scroll bar to value bigger than 50. About two seconds, the robot is in control mode. You can tap the arrow buttons to control the robot walking.

description.text:

Here is a set of mounts to go on 2020 aluminium printer frames. It clicks over onto the frame. I have just updated all of the files to be a snug fit. There are versions with and without a locking clip. It clicks on well and does not really need the locking clip for small items.

odd is the polygon that has side 1

We recently purchased a new lead and didn't have a dog poop bag holder for it.

I designed this one using Fusion360.

It is a simple design inspired by some of the others on Thingiverse and some commercial ones that I already had on other leads.

About the design:

BAGS

  • Designed for bag rolls that are about 32mm in diameter and 60mm in length
  • There is about 2mm tolerance on both of these dimensions

LEAD

  • Designed for leads about 25mm wide and 2mm thick
  • There is not a lot of tolerance on this
  • My lead is quite firm nylon and it seems to hold quite well; not so sure on a cotton blend lead

Feel free to leave comments and let me now if this works for you also.

UPDATE:
I've added v2 design files. The changes are:

  1. Removed fillet on lid and added small knobs to allow better grip

  2. Add a "full of poop bag hook" to the main body.

It occurred to me when out walking today that it'd be a good idea to have somewhere to store the full poop bag until I could find a rubbish bin.

I've not printed v2 so the hook may/may not work!

This model takes a standard credit card size plastic card.

I also have a printed plastic card design to fit this holder, see https://cards.aa.net.uk/

Three files: the whole thing (unlikely to print); Base with alignment pegs; Top with alignment holes. Easy to assemble with a spot of glue.

It is in OpenSCAD, and has a load of variables and comments so you can tweak the design if you need.

title: Hictop 3DP-17 z-rod top spacer for auto levelling z by g-code

description.text:
Very simple spacers (also makes a handy quick test print) to put over the z rods so that you can auto level the z plane by raising the z-axis to the top and 'bumping' into the top. Be very careful to ensure that your z-axis will travel all the way to the top without fouling, hitting or chopping anything. The effect of going slightly beyond the printer z maximum causes the steppers to skip but it leaves the z plane as level as the top of your printer. So also check that the top of your printer is level or square compared to the rest (you can compare a spirit level at the top and bottom.

I then added the following g-code to my slicer which homes, bumps z and then homes again (very important to re-home after bumping z) and does G29 bed levelling. It also heats the bed and nozzle in parallel. The nozzle is heated as far as possible without creating ooze during G29. Finally it heats the nozzle to 180 and does a good extrude and wipe at the front of the bed before starting to print.

!!! CHECK AND UNDERSTAND BEFORE USING - YOU NEED TO UPDATE TO THE LIMITS OF YOUR PRINTER !!!

https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B_5CzAtDHu6pMkNQWnAzeW16WkU/view?usp=sharing

!!! USE AT YOUR OWN RISK !!!

title: Yet Another Mosfet mount for the Anet A8
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Another Anet A8 mosfet mount. I wanted to design my own using my editor of choice called OpenSCAD [1]. The design file is attached. The entire design is fully parametrised so you can simply change a variable at the top of the file and the design will rebuild accordingly. I have included two stl files for the mosfet board to be mounted either vertically or horizontally; to do this only requires swapping two variables around: mosLctrs and mosWctrs.

UPDATE 18/05/2017 - Don't make the mistake I did. The gap between the Mosfet board and the Anet board's SD Card was so small I couldn't get the card in our out! I have re-done the STL files and the OpenSCAD so there is a much bigger space. If you mount your Mosfet below the Anet Mainboard however, then this won't be a problem.

The through-holes are for 3mm cap-head screws (~20mm in length). The base of the bracket has clearance holes to accept the entire cap head end of the screw so the bracket should sit flush on the Anet frame.

The look is based on the two remix links above. Thanks for the ideas. I hope people like the OpenSCAD version. If you have a different mosfet board with the mounting centres in different places this is the design file to start from.

path = Paths[0];

A remix (actually I had to rebuild it, but it's still based on the design) of mathgrrl's design, rescaled to fit the 1910 expansion with its much more pleasantly sized cards.  I've included the SketchUp files for further remixing.  
There's a version with squared corners and one with rounded corners.  The latter is certainly more appealing but if you prefer the former have a ball.  You can also print it without the inset and just have the letters as an engraving if you don't have dualstrusion, but it'll look so much nicer with the inset dualstruded into it.

Note that this is sized for the 1910 expansion cards.  If you have the original recipe cards, a) get the 1910 expansion, it's so much more comfortable to work with full sized cards! and b) if you really don't want to, scale this down in the X and Y axes (but ideally not the Z) by 0.79 before printing.

title: HORSTMANN AND QUAST HQ-17 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (35.99g thrust @3V )

description.text:
This drone propeller was inspired and designed by using the HORSTMANN AND QUAST HQ-17 airfoil. All tests were performed on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Tester All results can be checked below.

It was printed at a slow speed, using a 0.2 nozzle at 0.04mm layer height. I cleaned the print using a Precision Knife

After this, I then got to finish the propeller using a 400 grit sandpaper.

Here are the measurements for a few voltage presets (you can also check these out in the images):

  • 1.5V => 11.65 grams
  • 2V => 16.86 grams
  • 2.5V => 28.73 grams
  • 3V => 35.99 grams

The files you can download contain all the pictures taken during the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the STL files and the SLDPRT files. If you want to have some fun with this propeller, make sure you get a 8520 coreless motor.

Use the SLDPRT extension files, in case you desire to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Note: The airfoil plotted using the matplotlib library in python.

Hello!

This is a simple drop style coffee pod dispenser (keurig cups in my case). Load it from above and they'll stack up. Remove one from the bottom for consumption!

It can be fairly large depending on your needs. I split it up into 2 main parts the bottom dispensing component and the holding cylinders. The dispensing section is about 1 K cup tall, the cylinders are designed to be 15cm tall but nothing will stop you from adjusting the Z scale to fit your needs. I simply hot-glued the sections together and stacked the cylinders.

It's basically a hollow cylinder with a cut out at the bottom. There is also a cut slit going down the front so you can see how many pods are left.

I've loaded it up and it will stand on it's own, but I've design it with a flat portion so it can be attached to a wall (with sticky tack?) or magnetically attached to something (in my case a dish washer).

Enjoy!
